  "bib_entries": {
    "9480290": {
      "title": "Hormonal regulation of rapidly labelled ribonucleic acid in mammary cells in vitro",
      "abstract": "Abstract Insulin and prolactin stimulate the rate of incorporation of 3H-uridine into rapidly labeled nuclear RNA in mammary epithelial cells in organ culture. Since these hormones do not significantly alter the pool size and specific activity of uridine triphosphate, these effects appear to represent increased rates of RNA synthesis. These RNAs consist of 45 S and 32 S preribosomal RNA and heterogeneous, short lived RNA whose base composition is DNA-like. The hormonal stimulations result in an effective increase in the preribosomal RNA processed into 28 S and 18 S ribosomal RNA. The magnitude of prolactin's stimulation of RNA labeling is greater upon the ribosomal RNA than upon the preribosomal RNA, which suggests that prolactin may stimulate the ribosomal RNA-processing reactions. RNA synthesis was stimulated by prolactin only in daughter epithelial cells formed in vitro and previously treated with hydrocortisone, and this action of prolactin required the synergistic action of insulin. The stimulatory effect of prolactin on the synthesis of nuclear RNA was observed within 30 min, preceding the previously demonstrated increase in cytoplasmic ribosome concentration and the induction of specific milk proteins, and appears to represent an early effect of this hormone."
    },
    "36524943": {
      "title": "Estimates of parenchymal, stromal and lymph node deoxyribonucleic acid in mammary glands of C3H/Crgl/2 mice",
      "abstract": "Abstract The DNA content of intact and mammary gland (MG)-free segments of #4 pads of virgin and lactating C3H/Crg 1 2 female mice was determined. The DNA of inguinal MG lymph nodes was also estimated. The DNA of the MG-free-pad did not change between the virgin and lactational states; MG-DNA in the intact virgin and lactating fat pads was 23% and 89% of the total DNA, respectively. In lactating mice, MG-DNA increased 27-fold over that present in virgin mice. Inguinal lymph node DNA was 8.5 times greater than the MG-DNA of virgins and about 31% as high as the MG-DNA of the lactating gland."
    },
    "24921806": {
      "title": "Some effects of prolactin, insulin and hydrocortisone on RNA synthesis by mouse mammary gland, in vitro",
      "abstract": "Abstract It has been shown with explants of mouse mammary glands that non-secretory epithelial cells which contain hydrocortisone-induced rough endoplasmic reticulum can be converted into secretory cells by prolactin and insulin. Hydrocortisone does not detectably stimulate RNA synthesis by the epithelial cells, but prolactin-stimulated RNA synthesis is necessary for this conversion. Prolactin also stimulates RNA synthesis in mammary epithelial cells which have not been exposed to hydrocortisone and are unable to make secretory proteins in response to prolactin and insulin. Some mechanistic implications of this phenomenon are discussed."
    }
  }
}